The error message you're encountering, "TypeError at /blog/1/ blog() got an unexpected keyword argument 'id'", typically occurs in web frameworks like Django or Flask when you are trying to pass an unexpected keyword argument to a view function or method.

In this specific case, it seems you are trying to access a blog post with an 'id' of 1, and the view function for the '/blog/1/' URL is not expecting an 'id' as a keyword argument. The view function may be defined with a different set of arguments or keyword arguments.

To resolve this issue, you should review the code for your view function that handles the '/blog/1/' URL and ensure it is defined to accept an 'id' argument. For example, in Django, your view function might look something like this:

python
def blog(request, id): # Your view logic here

Make sure that 'id' is defined as a parameter in your view function. If it's supposed to be a part of the URL pattern, make sure your URL pattern is correctly configured to capture the 'id' value. For example:

python
path('blog/<int:id>/', views.blog, name='blog_detail')

Ensure that your URL pattern includes the 'id' parameter, and the view function's signature matches the expected arguments.

If you provide more context or code related to your specific situation, I can give you more targeted assistance.

fields.title: The Ultimate Guide to Buying the Best House for You
fields.content:
The site wisely points out that, despite the "excitable tweets" there has been no official confirmation from Apple itself.

Plus, the latest rumour torrent appears to be a repeat of previous, similar claims.

The site adds: "And a purchase has never materialised."

Elsewhere, crypto commentators say that Apple is too brand conscious and unlikely to do anything so controversial, writes Bitcoinist.

But, according to the same site, in May 2021 Apple posted a job seeking a business development manager dealing with "alternative payments".

Applicants were expected to have had more than five years of experience working with alternative payment providers, including cryptocurrency.

Apple has proceeded cautiously with cryptocurrencies, reports news agency Reuters.

The company banned cryptocurrency wallets from its App Store in 2014, but later reversed the decision and now allows them.

However, Apple bans mining for cryptocurrencies on iPhones and does not allow its Apple Card credit card to be used to buy digital currencies.

The Driller is a team leader in charge during the process of well drilling. The term is commonly used in the context of an oil well drilling rig. Driller comes after the Toolpusher in the Rig crew hierarchy. Toolpusher takes the operation orders from the Company-man. Toolpusher then supervises these order to the driller and the rest of the drilling crew and gets the job done. While Toolpusher, driller and the drilling crew generally belong to the Drilling contractor company, Company-man is the employee of the operator company.
